			<p class="bodySubTitle">Services</p>
			<p class="bodyText">
				Below is a listing of some services offered through the Puerto Rico Medicaid program if you qualify. 
				The Puerto Rico Medicaid program may place requirements on services including prior authorization (which means you or your doctor may be required to submit information to prove why you need certain drugs or medical procedures before they will be covered) or limitations like covering a maximum number of doctor visits.
				Please use the contact information provided to obtain a complete list of services. 
				<ul class="bodyText">
					<li><span class="bold">Clinic Services:</span> A wide range of healthcare services including services for prevention or treatment of health conditions or illnesses, surgery, and other care provided in a centralized facility. </li>
					<li><span class="bold">Dental Services:</span> Services provided by a dentist or dental assistant to diagnose, prevent and treat conditions of the mouth, teeth, and face. </li>
					<li><span class="bold">Diagnostic Services:</span> Services used to identify a disease based on signs and symptoms. Tools to identify a disease can include blood and urine tests.</li>
					<li><span class="bold">Early and Periodic Screening, Diagnostic &amp; Treatment Services (EPSDT):</span>Regularly scheduled screenings to identify physical and mental conditions and vision, hearing, and dental problems for people 20 years or younger. Also includes treatment of problems identified through screening regardless of whether that treatment is otherwise part of the Medicaid program.</li>
					<li><span class="bold">Emergency Hospital Services:</span> Services provided in a hospital emergency department to treat illnesses or injuries that are medical emergencies.</li>
					<li><span class="bold">Home Health Services:</span> A wide range of services performed at someone's home. They can include skilled and non-skilled services, part-time nursing care, different types of therapy (e.g. PT, OT, speech and audiology), help with activities of daily living and homemaker services such as cleaning and meal preparation.</li>
					<li><span class="bold">Inpatient Hospital Services:</span> Any services that a person might receive at a hospital while they are staying overnight. These could include services from a doctor or nurse, lab work, surgery, drugs, and food and bed.</li>
					<li><span class="bold">Lab and X-ray Services:</span> Services such as blood and urine tests and x-ray images ordered by a medical professional to screen for or diagnose a medical condition. </li>
					<li><span class="bold">Nursing Facility Services:</span> Skilled nursing, rehabilitation, and other services provided in a facility to help people with illness, injuries, or other disabilities to recover or to improve, and to provide long term care to those who need support with daily activities such as bathing, dressing and eating.</li>
					<li><span class="bold">Physicians Services:</span> Healthcare services, such as office visits, provided by a licensed doctor. </li>
					<li><span class="bold">Prescribed Drugs:</span> Drugs that a person can get only if a doctor (or another authorized healthcare provider) gives permission for them through a prescription. </li>
				</ul>
			</p>
